    <title>Using <code>data-</code> Attributes to Style the Title Attribute</title>
    <link href="http://adamnbowen.github.com/blog/2011/08/14/using-data--attributes-to-style-the-title-attribute/"/>
    <updated>2011-08-14T03:43:00-04:00</updated>
    <id>http://adamnbowen.github.com/blog/2011/08/14/using-data--attributes-to-style-the-title-attribute</id>
    <content type="html">&lt;!--- The example CSS --&gt;


&lt;p&gt;&lt;link href=&quot;http://adamnbowen.github.com/examples/data-title/example.css&quot; rel=&quot;stylesheet&quot;&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;!--- The example JavaScript --&gt;


&lt;script src=&quot;http://adamnbowen.github.com/examples/data-title/example.js&quot;&gt;&lt;/script&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Sometimes, I want to be able to style how browsers treat the &lt;code&gt;title&lt;/code&gt; tag. Most of the time, I don't condone overriding browser defaults with JavaScript, but I can see some potential uses for this technique---for example, you might wish to use a bigger font, or display the &lt;code&gt;title&lt;/code&gt; more prominently, or perhaps you simple want it to appear instantly, instead of after a delay.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h2&gt;Disclaimer&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Like all ventures into the land of html5, CSS and JavaScript, this may in fact be a terrible idea. I &lt;em&gt;do&lt;/em&gt; think this at least stands the chance of being a &quot;better&quot; solution than some others, as it&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Avoids extra markup&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;works just fine without JavaScript (as in, nothing bad happens if JavaScript is disabled)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;uses html5 &lt;strong&gt;semantics&lt;/strong&gt;, but &lt;em&gt;does not rely on&lt;/em&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://developers.whatwg.org/elements.html#embedding-custom-non-visible-data-with-the-data-*-attributes&quot;&gt;html5 functionality&lt;/a&gt; (so we don't &lt;em&gt;have&lt;/em&gt; to lock out old browsers)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;However, there is one potential hangup---While screen readers will be fine (no JavaScript to worry about), there may be some accessibility problems with removing the &lt;code&gt;title&lt;/code&gt; attribute.  If this is an issue, you could potentially replace the &lt;code&gt;data-title&lt;/code&gt; attribute with a new &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;span&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; element or something.  This will be a bit of extra work for your JavaScript, but should have no potential accessibility hangups.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So with that out of the way, let's get started.&lt;/p&gt;

